[Headnote: FRAG. 7. DESONELL AND HER TWINS REACH LAND.]

  [Sidenote:
  Desonell and her twin babes reach land. She stills her crying
  child,]

  Wyndes and weders hathe hir dryuen,
  That in a forest she is aryuen,
    Where wylde bestys were.                            1845
  The se was ebbe and went hem fro
  And left hir and hir chyldren two
    [Alo]ne without any fere.                           1848
  Hir one chylde began to wepe,
  The lady awoke out of hir slepe
    And sayde, aEuro~be styll, my dere,                      1851
  Ihesu Cryste hathe sent vs lande,
  Yf there be any Crysten man at hande,
    We shall haue socoure here.aEuro(TM)                        1854

  [Sidenote:
  goes up a mountain, and sits down.]

  The carefull lady then was blythe,
  To the londe she went full swythe,
    As fast as she myght.                               1857
  Tyll the day began to sprynge,
  Foules on trees merely gan synge
    Delicyous notes on hyght.                           1860
  To a hyll went that lady fre,
  Where she was ware of a cyte
    With toures fayre and bryght.                       1863
  Therof I-wys she was fayne,
  She set hir downe, as I herd sayne,
    Hir chyldren for to dyght.                          1866




NOTES.


PAGE 1, line 12. Cf. ll. 118, 187, 190, 198, 558, 924, 1924, 2183. So in
_Eglamour_ (Thornton Romances), l. 408:

  aEuro~The boke of Rome thus can telle,aEuro(TM)

and _The Erl of Tolouse_, ed. LA1/4dtke, l. 1219:

  aEuro~Yn Rome thys geste cronyculyd ys.aEuro(TM)

See HalliwellaEuro(TM)s and LA1/4dtkeaEuro(TM)s notes to these passages. I agree with both
of them, that an expression like that does not earnestly refer the
reader to a Latin or Italian source of the story; there is evidently no
difference at all between _in Rome_ and _in romance_.

p. 1, l. 15. _wyght_ has been inserted instead of _dowghtty_ in order to
restore the rhyme with _hyght_, _knyght_, _myght_; cf. _Havelok_, ed.
Skeat, l. 344:

  aEuro~He was fayr man and wicth.aEuro(TM)

p. 1, l. 17 = _Ipomadon_, l. 63. Parallel passages to this hyperbolic
expression are collected in KA�lbingaEuro(TM)s note to this line (p.A 364).

p. 1, l. 24. We find the same idea as here, viz. that nobody can resist
the will of God, who has power over death and life, in _Sir Tristrem_,
ll. 236A ff.:

  aEuro~Azat leuedi, nouE�t to lain,
  For soA3/4e ded is sche!
  Who may be ogain?
  As god wil, it schal be,
  VnbliA3/4e.aEuro(TM)

p. 2, l. 28. I have not met with the verb _fesomnen_ anywhere else, and
it is not mentioned in Stratmann and MA�tzner. Halliwell, Dictionary,
p.A 354, explains it by aEuro~feoffed, gave in fee,aEuro(TM) doubtless regarding this
very passage, although he doesnaEuro(TM)t cite it; might _fesomnyd_ not be a
corruption from _sesyd_? cf. _Havelok_, ll. 250A f.:

  aEuro~Azat he ne dede al Engelond
  Sone sayse intil his hond.aEuro(TM)

Hall writes to me on this word as follows: _fesomnyd_ is, IA am
convinced, not a word at all, but a scribeaEuro(TM)s error for _festonyd_ or
_festnyd_ = confirmed, fixed. Comp. aEuro(TM)_And A3/4at ich hym wolde myd trewA3/4e
siker faste on honde_,aEuro(TM) Robert of Gloucester (Hearne), p.A 150. For this
use of _fasten, fastnen_, comp. aEuro(TM)_But my forwarde with A3/4e I festen on
A3/4is wyse_,aEuro(TM) Alliterative Poems, p.A 47, l. 327: aEuro(TM)_& folden fayth to A3/4at
fre, festned so harde_,aEuro(TM) Sir Gawayne, p.A 57, l. 1783: aEuro(TM)_And A3/4is forward,
in faith, IA festyn with hond_,aEuro(TM) Destruction of Troy, p.A 22, l. 636. See
also JamiesonaEuro(TM)s Scottish Dictionary, ii. p.A 216, under _to Fest_.

p. 2, l. 30. I am by no means sure that _fede_ is the original reading,
but I wasnaEuro(TM)t able to find a better word rhyming with _dedde_, _wede_;
even the _ne._ aEuro~feedaEuro(TM) means _pasture_, and that is what we expect here.

p. 2, l. 31. For my correction cf. LA1/4dtkeaEuro(TM)s note to _The Erl of
Tolouse_, l. 199, sub 2; _Eglam._, l.A 26:

  aEuro~That was a maydyn as whyte as fome,aEuro(TM)

_Ib._ l. 683:

  aEuro~Crystyabelle as whyte as fome,aEuro(TM)

where the _Percy Folio MS._ reads:

  aEuro~Christabell that was as faire as sunn;aEuro(TM)

_Chronicle of England_, l. 75 f.:

  aEuro~Ant nomeliche to thy lemmon,
  That ys wyttore then the fom.aEuro(TM)

p. 2, l. 50. The alteration of _And_ and _bee_ into _An_ and _see_
seemed necessary; _sayment_ is like Fr. _essaiement_, Lat.
_exagimentum_.

p. 3, l. 59. Cf. l. 1216 f. and _The Lyfe of Ipomydon_, ed. KA�lbing,
l. 1795:

  aEuro~If thou hyr haue, thou shalt hyr bye.aEuro(TM)

p. 3, l. 77 f. As half of the stanza is lost, it is impossible to make
out to whom _they_ refers. Nor do I believe that l. 78 is correct,
especially as to _chaunce_.

p. 3, l. 79. Cf. _Ipomadon_, ed. KA�lbing, l. 8123:

  aEuro~A myle wyth in the Grekes see.aEuro(TM)

p. 3, l. 80. _in an yle_ is certainly the correct reading; _mauyle_ was
introduced by a scribe who supposed it to be the giantaEuro(TM)s name; but that
is mentioned some twenty lines later.

p. 5, l. 136. The correction of _lyght_ into _ryght_ I owe to Hall, who
refers me to the legend of _Sancta Maria Egyptiaca_; cf. f. i. BarbouraEuro(TM)s
_Legends of Saints_, ed. Horstmann, I. p.A 143A ff.

p. 6, l. 153. _nowyd_ = aEuro~anoyedaEuro(TM) gives a poor sense. Hall suggests
_nowtyd_; cf. E. D. S., No. 6, RayaEuro(TM)s _North Country Words_, p.A 59,
_note_, to push, strike or soar, with the horn, as a bull or ram,aEuro(TM) ab.
A.S. _huitan_, ejusdem significationis. The word might then mean
aEuro~spurred.aEuro(TM)

p. 6, l. 171 = l. 596. This alliterative binding is a very frequent one;
cf. _Sir Orfeo_, ed. Zielke, p.A 9.

p. 7, l. 188. The same rhyme, which I have restored here, occurs
l. 559A f.

p. 7, l. 190. _Yt tellythe_ = _Yt is told_; cf. LA1/4dtke, note to _The Erl
of Tolouse_, l. 1070, and Sarrazin, note to _Octavian_, l. 1749.

p. 9, l. 236. I was about to write, _Crystyn men thow they were_,
referring this line to the guardians of the lions; but, no doubt, HallaEuro(TM)s
reconstruction of the line, which I have put into the text, is far
better.

p. 9, l. 237. _Hys browys wexe bla_, i.e. he turned pale, he was struck
with fear; cf. _bloo askes_, P. Pl., l. 1553, and the German _aschfahl_.
Quite a similar expression occurs in _Perceval_, l. 687A f.:

  aEuro~Now sone of that salle wee see,
  Whose browes schalle blakke.aEuro(TM)

_Ib._ l. 1056:

  aEuro~His browes to blake.aEuro(TM)

p. 9, l. 245. Though _syghyng_ gives no offence, still it may be, that
the author has written _syngyng_, and the scribe was wrong in altering
it; cf. ZupitzaaEuro(TM)s note to _Guy_, l. 5424.

p. 9, l. 251. Cf. l. 802, 1204, _Ipomadon_, l. 6481 f.:

  aEuro~Your nece of Calabyre, that lady clere,
  Ys bovnden wyth a fendes fere.aEuro(TM)

_ReliquiA| AntiquA|_, i. p. 241:

  aEuro~He seith bi niE�te and eke bi day,
  That hy beth fendes ifere.aEuro(TM)

p. 10, l. 265 f. The reading of these two lines is quite destroyed by
the careless scribe. My correction is not more than an attempt to
restore the rhyme.

p. 10, l. 277 ff. There is nothing in TorrentaEuro(TM)s words which could lead
the princess to a conclusion like that. IA think that after l. 276 one
stanza is wanting.

p. 11, l. 286-8. As to the contents of these lines, KA�lbing refers me to
_Englische studien_, vol. IV. p.A 133 f., where F. Liebrecht mentions a
passage in _Sir Beves of Hamtoun_, according to which a kingaEuro(TM)s
daughter,--if she is a pure virgin,--can never be hurt by a lion. Here
we have another proof for this remarkable bit of folk-lore.

p. 11, l. 292 = l. 329.

p. 11, l. 303 = l. 342.

p. 11, l. 305. I am not quite sure whether I was right in substituting
the princeaEuro(TM)s name--which is mentioned once more, the first time, as it
were, l. 341--for the name of his fatheraEuro(TM)s kingdom; but I didnaEuro(TM)t see any
other way of restoring the rhyme.

p. 12, l. 311. Cf. l. 469 and SkeataEuro(TM)s note to _Sir Thopas_, l. 1927.

p. 12, l. 334. Instead of _he_ I should prefer to read _they_: Torrent
has just admonished the prisoners to cheerA up.

p. 13, l. 344. There must be something wrong in this line, because the
name of the third EarlaEuro(TM)s son is missing; to write _the third_ instead of
_of_ may not suffice to put the text right; even the names _Torren_ and
_Berweyne_ seem to me very suspicious.

p. 14, l. 379. Cf. _Ipomadon_, l. 4245, _for Crystys dede_; _Crystys_
was substituted by KA�lbing for _mannes_, which is clearly wrong; he
could as well have chosen _godes_.

p. 15, l. 393 ff. Cf. KA�lbingaEuro(TM)s note to _Tristrem_, l. 736.

p. 16, l. 427. Of this allusion to Veland, Halliwell treats in his
edition of _Sir Torrent_, p.A vii f. Cf. Zupitza, _Ein zeugnis fA1/4r die
Wieland-sage_, _Zeitschrift fA1/4r deutsches Alterthum_, Vol. XIX,
p.A 129A f.

p. 16, l. 429-31. The line which follows l. 429 in the MS. is
superfluous; it damages the metre; and the rhyme with l. 430 wonaEuro(TM)t do.
The old king wishes to say; aEuro~IA have seen the day when, if this sword
wielded by me fell on any one, he was considered done for, doomed to
death.aEuro(TM) Therefore l. 431, _IA fawght therfor I told_ has been corrected
into _Fawe they were I-told_. The scribe did not understand the
obsolescent word _fawe_ or _faye_, so he wrote the nearest word to it to
make sense, _I-told_ = aEuro~held, considered.aEuro(TM)--I. Hall.

p. 17, l. 458. Cf. BreulaEuro(TM)s note to _Sir Gowther_, l. 410.

p. 17, l. 465. Cf. l. 2061 f.

p. 20, l. 542. The scribe, who evidently didnaEuro(TM)t know the pretty rare
word _clow_, has spoilt it to _colod_, or _colvd_; the same rhyme,
_clouE�_, _drouE�_, _anouE�_ occurs in _Sir Tristrem_, l. 1761 ff. Nor did
the scribe know the word _swowe_ = aEuro~noise,aEuro(TM) and changed it to _swayne_;
cf. Hall. Dict., p.A 843: _He come to him with a swowe_.

p. 20, l. 543. _Of and on_, off and on, intermittently.

p. 21, l. 555. _schyld_ is not to the point here, Torrent having only
his sword at hand. The scribe has forgotten what he has said himself,
l. 526 and 549; cf. l. 652.

p. 21, l. 582-4. We meet with this description twice more in the poem,
ll. 1514-16, and ll. 1858-60.

p. 23, l. 640. On the meaning of _theff_, cf. KA�lbingaEuro(TM)s note to _Am. and
Amil._, l. 787.

p. 24, l. 659. _of Perowne_ is certainly wrong, as it does not agree
with the rhymes _stere_, _nere_, _fere_; but I donaEuro(TM)t know how to amend
the line.

p. 24, l. 662. _schere_ gives no meaning; I write _stere_ and translate,
There might nobody move further, _i.e._ the giant was brought to a
standstill in the glen.

p. 24, l. 665. Cf. ll. 434, 791.

p. 25, l. 688. Cf. _Eglam._, l. 324:

  aEuro~And to [the] herte hym bare.aEuro(TM)

The weak preterit tense of _berien_ is very rare; if _bere_ = A.S.
_beran_ sometimes has the same meaning, _i.e._ aEuro~to strike,aEuro(TM) the reason
is that A.S. _beran_ and Icel. _berja_ are confounded.

p. 25, l. 696. _woo_ can hardly stand for _wood_. It seems to me like a
last corruption of an old romance phrase, like _worthy inwith wall
(woE�e)_; possibly the line was simply so: _Thus in II journeys Torrent
so_.--Hall.

p. 25, l. 700. On the use of M.E. _fote_ as a plural see ZupitzaaEuro(TM)s note
to _Guy_, l. 598.

p. 26, l. 722. Hall suggests, the original phrase may have been: _pomely
